  "prompt": "What is fungal laccase?",
  "response": "Fungal laccase is an enzyme produced by various fungi that belongs to the class of oxidoreductases. Here are key details about fungal laccase:\n\n1. Classification\n- Multi-copper oxidase enzyme\n- Found in many white-rot fungi\n- Belongs to the blue copper protein family\n\n2. Structural characteristics\n- Contains four copper atoms in its active site\n- Molecular weight typically ranges from 60-70 kDa\n- Contains multiple copper centers\n\n3. Primary function\n- Catalyzes oxidation of phenolic and non-phenolic compounds\n- Reduces molecular oxygen to water\n- Facilitates substrate degradation through electron transfer\n\n4. Key properties\n- High redox potential\n- Broad substrate specificity\n- Works at ambient temperatures\n- Tolerant to various pH conditions\n\n5. Biological roles\n- Lignin degradation\n- Pigment formation\n- Fungal cell wall modification\n- Pathogen defense mechanism\n\n6. Industrial/biotechnological applications\n- Bioremediation\n- Textile industry\n- Paper pulp processing\n- Biosensor development\n- Pharmaceutical synthesis\n\n7. Sources\n- White-rot fungi\n- Brown-rot fungi\n- Some ascomycetes and basidiomycetes\n\nFungal laccase is significant for its versatile enzymatic properties and potential biotechnological applications.",
